With a thrill-kill philosophy somewhere between the Dionysian and the Nietzchean, Monster Magnet&#039;s superhuman cartoon reality becomes ever more enveloping with each subsequent album. And from the first chord of God Says No, you know you are in for a wild ride. "Melt" finds head Magnet Dave Wyndorf, in his "world of pills" wondering "how the world should have cried on the day Jack Kirby died". The obvious first single, "Heads Explode", rolls along with same mock mod-fervour as "See You In Hell" (from Powertrip) before detonating into absolute mayhem at the chorus. Throughout, Wyndorf plays themoreÃƒÂ¢?Ã‚Â¦ arch-devil&#039;s advocate, switching between adulation and annihilation of his bitch/goddess foil (on tracks like "Doomsday" and "Queen Of You"). "Gravity Well" is as raw as it gets, bare bones blues that sounds like a version of Son House&#039;s "John The Revelator" recorded on the wrong side of the tracks. And, as the high priest of all that he surveys, Wyndorf faces his own Judgment Day on the sin-soaked ramble of "God Says No", before finally coming down on the side of the damned. Devotees will already know what to expect: tunes to make your head explode.

Enjoy! :)
